                </section>

                <section id="wattage" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">3. Output Wattage Selection: Matching PD Specs to Your Target Market Segment</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">For OEM product planners, output wattage determines which market segment your power bank serves — from budget smartphone users (18-20W) to premium laptop owners (65-100W). mAh tells you <em>how much</em> power; wattage tells you <em>how fast</em> it delivers. Both matter equally.</p>
                    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
                        <table class="w-full border border-slate-200 rounded-xl">
                            <thead class="bg-brandBlue text-white">
                                <tr>
                                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-black uppercase text-xs">Output Wattage</th>
                                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-black uppercase text-xs">OEM Product Positioning</th>
                                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-black uppercase text-xs">Target Device Segment</th>
                                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-black uppercase text-xs">FOB Cost Impact</th>
                                </tr>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold">10-12W (5V/2A)</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Entry-level, budget retail. Legacy USB-A only. Not recommended for new OEM products in 2026.</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Earbuds, smartwatch, giveaways</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Baseline — lowest BOM</td></tr>
                                <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold">18-20W (USB-C PD)</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Entry smartphone tier. Minimum viable spec for any new 2026 OEM power bank.</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">iPhone fast charge (0-50% in ~30 min)</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">+$0.50-1.00 vs 10W</td></tr>
                                <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold text-brandBlue">30W (USB-C PD + PPS)</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Flagship phone tier — highest volume premium segment. PPS enables Samsung Super Fast Charging and iPhone 27W.</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Galaxy S Ultra, iPhone Pro Max, Pixel Pro</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">+$1.00-2.00 vs 20W ★</td></tr>
                                <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold">45-65W (USB-C PD 3.0)</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Tablet/ultrabook tier — fastest-growing OEM segment driven by EU USB-C laptop mandate from April 2026.</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">iPad Pro, MacBook Air, Surface, Dell XPS</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">+$3.00-5.00 vs 30W</td></tr>
                                <tr><td class="p-3 font-bold">100W+ (PD 3.1 EPR)</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Laptop replacement tier — premium margin, lower volume. Requires EPR-rated e-marker cable in-box.</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">MacBook Pro 16", gaming laptops, workstations</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">+$8.00-15.00 vs 65W</td></tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-brandBlue/10 border-l-4 border-brandBlue p-5 rounded-r-xl">
                        <h4 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">OEM Product Planning Rule: Market the Wattage Your Customer's Device Actually Uses</h4>
                        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">A 100W power bank won't charge an iPhone faster than a 30W bank — the iPhone caps at ~27W regardless of the power source. For OEM brands, this means: <strong>marketing claims should reference the end device's actual maximum input, not the charger's theoretical ceiling.</strong> A 100W power bank marketed to iPhone users generates returns and negative reviews when customers realize they paid for wattage they can't use. For smartphone-dominant markets, 20-30W output is the optimal balance of BOM cost and marketable performance. Reserve 65W+ for product lines specifically targeting laptop and tablet users.</p>
                    </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section id="ports" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">4. Port Configuration for OEM Product Lines: USB-C PD, USB-A & Qi2 Wireless</h2>
                    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">USB-C PD — Mandatory Baseline for 2026</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Every new OEM power bank design in 2026 must include bi-directional USB-C with PD 3.0 minimum (PD 3.1 recommended for 65W+). The EU Common Charger Directive makes USB-C mandatory for all new devices. OEM specification priority: <strong>bi-directional PD</strong> (the port handles both input recharge and output charging), with PPS support for Samsung and iPhone fast-charge compatibility. <a href="/blog/usb-c-pd-fast-charging-guide/" class="text-brandBlue hover:underline">USB-C PD Fast Charging Guide →</a></p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">USB-A — Legacy Compatibility Port</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Include one USB-A port (10-18W) for backward compatibility with Micro-USB accessories, wireless earbuds cases, and markets where USB-A cables still dominate (Southeast Asia, Africa, Latin America). Minimal BOM cost adder. For premium EU/US SKUs, a USB-C-only design with an included C-to-A adapter reduces BOM and simplifies the industrial design. Not recommended as the primary output port on any new 2026 OEM product.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">Qi2 Magnetic Wireless — Premium Add-On Tier</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Qi2 magnetic output (15W, N52H magnets) adds $2-4 to BOM but enables a distinct premium SKU tier. Wireless efficiency is inherently lower (70-80%) vs wired (85-92%), and Qi2 generates more heat — both points must be managed in product spec claims to avoid returns. Qi2.2 (25W) is the emerging premium standard. OEM best practice: offer Qi2 wireless as a feature on 10,000mAh+ models, not as a standalone wireless-only SKU. <a href="/blog/qi2-vs-magsafe-guide/" class="text-brandBlue hover:underline">Qi2 vs MagSafe Guide →</a></p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">Built-in Cables — Niche Differentiation Feature</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Integrated USB-C or Lightning cables add $1-3 to BOM and create a unique SKU differentiator for travel/commuter segments. Key OEM specification: demand <strong>reinforced strain relief rated for 10,000+ bend cycles</strong> — the built-in cable is the single highest-failure component. If the cable fails, the entire unit becomes e-waste, directly impacting warranty costs and brand reputation. Include cable replacement terms in the warranty policy.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section id="features" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">5. 2026 OEM Differentiators: GaN, Pass-Through & Semi-Solid-State Technology</h2>
                    <div class="space-y-4">
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">GaN (Gallium Nitride) Technology</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">GaN power banks are smaller, cooler, and more efficient (90-92% conversion vs 80-85%). The size difference is significant — a GaN 10,000mAh bank is noticeably slimmer. Worth the modest premium. <a href="/blog/what-is-gan-charger/" class="text-brandBlue hover:underline">Learn more about GaN →</a></p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">Digital Battery Display</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">LED dots (4 lights = 25% each) are imprecise. A digital percentage display tells you exactly how much power remains — critical when deciding whether to bring the bank or charge it before leaving. Look for LCD or TFT displays showing both percentage and charging wattage.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">Pass-Through Charging</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Can the power bank charge your devices while being recharged itself? This is essential for overnight use — plug the bank into the wall, plug your phone into the bank, and both are full by morning. Not all power banks support this; verify before buying.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">Semi-Solid-State Battery</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">The newest battery technology: gel electrolyte replaces most of the flammable liquid in traditional Li-ion cells. Benefits include <strong>2-3× longer lifespan</strong> (1,000-2,000 cycles), <strong>dramatically safer</strong> (no fire when punctured), and <strong>ultra-thin designs</strong> (as thin as 6.8mm). Premium price but genuinely better technology. <a href="/blog/semi-solid-state-power-bank-oem/" class="text-brandBlue hover:underline">Read our semi-solid-state guide →</a></p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section id="airline" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">6. Battery Logistics Compliance: UN38.3, IATA Wh Limits & Air Freight Documentation</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">For importers and OEM brands, lithium battery shipping compliance is a supply chain requirement — not just a traveler's concern. UN38.3 certification, IATA watt-hour limits, and proper DG documentation determine whether your shipment clears customs or gets held at the port. Here are the rules governing power bank logistics as of 2026:</p>
                    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
                        <table class="w-full border border-slate-200 rounded-xl">
                            <thead class="bg-brandBlue text-white">
                                <tr>
                                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-black uppercase text-xs">Rule</th>
                                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-black uppercase text-xs">Requirement</th>
                                </tr>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold">Carry-on ONLY</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Power banks must be in carry-on luggage. <strong>NEVER in checked bags.</strong> If a fire starts in the cabin, crew can respond. In the cargo hold, it's undetectable.</td></tr>
                                <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold">Under 100Wh (~27,000mAh)</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">No airline approval needed. Unlimited quantity within reasonable personal use (typically up to 10-20). Most consumer power banks fall in this category.</td></tr>
                                <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold">100-160Wh</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Airline approval required. Limited to 2 per passenger. Covers large laptop power banks and professional equipment.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td class="p-3 font-bold">Over 160Wh</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm"><strong>Prohibited</strong> on passenger aircraft. Cargo-only with dangerous goods declaration.</td></tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-brandBlue/5 rounded-xl p-5 border border-brandBlue/10">
                        <p class="font-black text-brandBlue text-sm uppercase mb-2">How to Calculate Watt-Hours (Wh)</p>
                        <p class="text-slate-700 font-mono text-sm mb-2"><strong>Wh = (mAh × Voltage) ÷ 1,000</strong></p>
                        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">For a 20,000mAh power bank at 3.7V: (20,000 × 3.7) ÷ 1,000 = <strong>74Wh</strong> — well under the 100Wh limit.<br>For a 27,000mAh bank: (27,000 × 3.7) ÷ 1,000 = <strong>99.9Wh</strong> — right at the limit.</p>
                    </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

